{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609401"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:48:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:48:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16106"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16106","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16106"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.79,0,0,0.18,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8797"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74151"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8797","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8797"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16106"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59642"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"10738"},{"type":"tags","id":"10741"},{"type":"tags","id":"10959"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21000"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21004"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74151"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESex chromosome aneuploidies are relatively common genetic conditions that occur when there are abnormal numbers of X or Y chromosomes. Many cases are identified through genetic testing or during investigations for infertility.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most common sex chromosome aneuploidy in humans?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["47,XXY","47,XYY","47,XXX","45,X","49,XXXXY"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E47,XXY\u003C/strong\u003E (Klinefelter syndrome) occurs in approximately 1 in 500-1,000 male births, making it the most common sex chromosome aneuploidy. It typically results from nondisjunction during meiosis in either parent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other sex chromosome aneuploidies occur less frequently:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E47,XYY\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in approximately 1 in 1,000 male births and is often associated with tall stature\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E47,XXX\u003C/strong\u003E (Triple X syndrome) occurs in approximately 1 in 1,000 female births and may have minimal clinical features\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E45,X\u003C/strong\u003E (Turner syndrome) occurs in approximately 1 in 2,000-2,500 female births and typically presents with short stature and primary amenorrhoea\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E49,XXXXY\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare variant of Klinefelter syndrome occurring in approximately 1 in 85,000-100,000 male births with more severe features\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMany cases of sex chromosome aneuploidies may go undiagnosed due to their relatively mild phenotypes compared to autosomal chromosome disorders. The presence of additional X chromosomes has less impact due to X-inactivation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Klinefelter syndrome (47,XXY) occurs in approximately 1 in 500-1,000 male births, making it the most common sex chromosome aneuploidy.","Sex chromosome aneuploidies often have milder phenotypes compared to autosomal aneuploidies due to X-inactivation and the low gene content of the Y chromosome.","Many cases of sex chromosome aneuploidy are diagnosed incidentally or remain undiagnosed due to subtle clinical features."],"references":["Orr B, Godek KM, Compton D. Aneuploidy. Curr Biol. 2015 Jun 29;25(13):R538-42. doi: 10.1016/j.cub.2015.05.010. PMID: 26126276; PMCID: PMC4714037.","Compton DA. Mechanisms of aneuploidy. Curr Opin Cell Biol. 2011 Feb;23(1):109-13. doi: 10.1016/j.ceb.2010.08.007. PMID: 20810265; PMCID: PMC2997176.","Mandrioli D, Belpoggi F, Silbergeld EK, Perry MJ. Aneuploidy: a common and early evidence-based biomarker for carcinogens and reproductive toxicants. Environ Health. 2016 Oct 12;15(1):97. doi: 10.1186/s12940-016-0180-6. PMID: 27729050; PMCID: PMC5059969.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59642"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16106"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59642"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T21:47:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T21:47:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8797"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74151"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"42","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/42"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Genetics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emed